Using R Packages
R and the open-source R packages installed1 on our SCE (Scientific Computing Environment; i.e. DaVinci) are validated and can be used to generate outputs for reporting. This means that any R package you can access with library without first installing it has been validated and can be safely used.

The version of R and associated set of packages are updated periodically as part of operational releases. The validation process obviates the need for double programming of the functionality of the package but users remain accountable for understanding the implementation of the methodology (e.g. solvers and defaults). You can learn more about validation here

How to use the validated R packages
There are two ways in which to load the installed packages on our SCE (i.e. DaVinci).

Validated R packages are pre-installed and can be loaded using
library(<package>)
The set of pre-installed packages are referred to as a bundle. When you select the version of R the most recent bundle will be selected. See here for more information on R bundle management.

Validated R packages are also hosted on the DaVinci instance of posit package manager which are aligned to the version of R being used and require users to install the package using
install.packages("<package>", repo = https://rspm.apps.dit-prdocp.novartis.net/validated-R-4.1.0/2023-11-10+MTI6MzYxMjs2RkMxRTZBMw, lib = "<local_path>")
Users should also select a repo snapshot via selecting a date in the setup tab to ensure reproducibility.

What if the R package (or specific version) you need for reporting is not already installed?
In this case, there are two options available to users with different time horizons and levels of user participation.

Option 1: Request a package as part of the SCE release cycle.
You can use the MELZI app to request your package. Note that the releases on our SCE take place with a frequency in the range of months and therefore the turnaround time can vary depending on the timing of the request with respect to the release cycle.


Option 2: Adhoc installation of a package for time-sensitive GxP activities
Note
You might encounter yourself in this situation if you need a package that is not on DaVinci, or you need a more recent version of package in DaVinci, and you can‚Äôt wait for the next DaVinci release

The process of adhoc validation of publicly available open source R packages is described in WP-8125598. The guidance here provides a specific example of how the work procedure may be implemented in practice, although it is not the only compliant way.

For the most common use case, in which the package originates from CRAN, the following code will install the package from a pre-specified posit package manager (PPM; previously RSPM) snapshot in go/rstudio.

Running the ad-hoc installation with brave
You can install the package that you need for GxP activities using the package brave which is available in DaVinci. brave is an internally developed package that apart from facilitating the adhoc installation of R packages, performs the packages‚Äô risk assessment in a semi-automated manner and provides a Risk Assessment form.

The function of interest from brave is adhocRequire. It will install the package in a temporary folder. The usage of the function is as follows:

# Navigate to the path of R program that generates your output

# Set this location as your working directory
setwd("<path of R program that generates your output>")

# Load the brave package
library(brave)

# Set your repository snapshot date
ref = 'default'

# Execute the adhoc installation
brave::adhocRequire("<package>", ref=ref) 

You must first navigate to the folder that contains the programs that will use this package, and set it as your working directory with setwd().

Then, you must set your repository snapshot date and run the adhocRequire() function.

TipHow to choose the repository snapshot date
This is configured using the ref argument in the brave package. There are three different options:

ref = "recent": the Posit Package Manager snapshot 2 days prior to today‚Äôs date. Note this install may require dependencies that are not compatible / available with the current DaVinci release
ref="<YYYY-MM-DD>": the Posit Package Manager snapshot form an specific date. Note this install may also require dependencies that are not compatible / available with the current DaVinci release.
ref = "default": the date of the snapshot used for the packages currently installed on DaVinci. This will help increase the chances of a successful install.
The {brave} package was developed by the SOS team to do most of the heavy lifting for you. It will download and install the package in a temporary folder, it will execute various checks, and perform the risk assessment.

This generates evidence in the form of various files that you may use to demonstrate that the package works as intended. It also creates an adhocRequire.rds file, which you need later.

ImportantadhocRequire.rds
You will need to add the generated adhocRequire.rds to source control as it contains the repository snapshot date used to install the package.

This will ensure that when your colleagues call the adhocRequire() the package gets installed from the same date as you did, ensuring reproducibility.

CautionHotfix for brave if using R-4.1.0 (R-bundle-Novartis/0.6-gomkl-2019a-R-4.1.0)
Understanding brave results
{brave} installs the package and its unit tests. It will then attempt to run them as well as the vignettes and examples that are part of the package. The outcome of these assessments is both printed to the console and stored in a .zip file. Ideally, you will see something akin to this:

{mmrm} initial risk assessment: medium
Package 'mmrm' installed with PPPM snapshot '2023-03-06'
Test results (TRUE=success):
  examples tests vignettes
1     TRUE  TRUE      TRUE
tests ran on platform: x86_64-pc-linux-gnu
using R version: R version 4.1.0 (2021-05-18)
see zip file '/home/doyleor1/R-4.1.0-mmrm-2023-03-06.zip' 
Review results and assess project impact

If one of the checks (examples, tests, vignettes) is negative (has a FALSE somewhere), the important piece is to understand the reason why it failed. Some errors are acceptable or benign, but others may negatively affect the package‚Äôs performance; search the information stored in the .zip file to ascertain the root cause of the problem. If you have a negative outcome and cannot make sense of it, reach out to the SOS team to discuss options and your next steps.

Understanding the Risk Profile
The risk assessment outcome is both printed out (see above) and produces a .docx file with name <status>-<package>-riskAssessment.docx. The status is one out of five possible alternatives as described here and users are required to follow the actions (if any) that have been outlined. Note that low and medium risk no further action is needed but for other outcomes further effort is required. Reach out to the SOS team if your risk is high, undetermined or ineligible.

Using the Package
To load the package add the following code to your R program that you want to run to generate your outputs. This R program should be co-located with the adhocRequire.rds file generated during the install process.

# Add these lines of code to your R program that will use the newly installed package
library(brave)

# load the package using the "pinned" setting which reads the 
# snapshot date from the `adhocRequire.rds` file
brave::adhocRequire("<package>", ref= "pinned") 

CautionHotfix for brave if using R-4.1.0 (R-bundle-Novartis/0.6-gomkl-2019a-R-4.1.0)
You should now be able to call functions from your newly installed packaged and you can treat this package in the same manner as those pre-installed on DaVinci, i.e. as a validated package.

Storing the Evidence
The collected evidence should be stored in a version-controlled location somewhere close to the final code that uses that package. For example, the study folder in GPS2 where your programs are or in the utils folder.

What to do if brave fails installing your package
Package dependencies incompatibilities
The main reason why brave could fail to install and load your package is due to package dependencies and its versions. For example, the package that you want to install, package_1, requires a version of package_2 of v2. The problem is that package_2 is already installed in DaVinci with v1, and it has already been loaded, so an error like this could appear on RStudio:

Error: package or namespace load failed for 'package_1' in loadnamespace(j <- i[[1L]], c(lib.loc, .libPaths()), versionCheck = vI[[j]]):
namespace 'package_2' v1 is already loaded, but >= v2 is required

In order to troubleshoot this, you will need to adhoc install both package_1 and package_2 with the correct versions. You can follow this steps to try to fix the problem:

Restart your RStudio R session (Session>Restart R)
Print your sessionInfo() to make sure none of the packages you are going to install are already loaded. If they are loaded, please restart your RStudio R session again.
Set your working directory to the folder were you have your programs
Select a snapshot date that has the correct version for both packages and assign it to the ref argument
Adhoc install package_2 (the dependency that causes the problem)
Make sure that the correct version of package_2 was loaded checking sessionInfo()
Adhoc install package_1
# First restart your session doing Session>Restart R
# Make sure that not package_1 or package_2 are loaded using sessionInfo()
# if they are loaded restart your session again

# Navigate to your folder and set your working directory
setwd("~/folder")

# Set a snapshot date
ref <- "2024-06-24"

# First, install the correct version of package_2 (the package dependency causing issues)
brave::adhocRequire("package_2", ref)

# Make sure that the correct version of package_2 was loaded checking sessionInfo()

# After that, you can do it for package_1, and there should be no depencies issues
brave::adhocRequire("package_1", ref)

{renv} issues
Warning
Remember that for GxP related activities, you must use packages installed in DaVinci bundles, as they have been risk-assessed and validated.

If you are using {renv} in your project, you might run into issues when using the adhoc installation using {brave} as they are not compatible. It can happen that if you are using {renv} in other project, it gets activated even if you are in a different folder/project. Some recommendations to avoid {renv}-related problems are:

Set your GxP related project folder as your working directory and restart your RStudio R session (Session>Restart R)
Use renv::deactivate() and restart your RStudio R session (Session>Restart R)
To completely remove renv from a project, call renv::deactivate(clean = TRUE). If you later want to use renv for this project, you‚Äôll need to start from scratch with renv::init().
